{"title": "The Man Makes the Weapon", "content": "If you think he's good at swordfights, wait till you see him do the dusting.\n\nTwo people are in a duel. One of them pulls a fairly traditional weapon... a sword, spear, maybe even a gun. His opponent (usually the protagonist) picks a relatively \"weak\" equivalent, something that's generally not lethal (something as dangerous as a broken bottle would rarely be seen in this trope). Sometimes, he may even go as far as to ignore real weapons that are lying around. He proceeds to kick the first guy's ass, showing off a clear difference in skill. The key to this trope, however, is skill. He doesn't win the fight due to the weapon being unconventional, quirky, or unexpected (like a stepladder). The weapon is generally analogous to the user's own preferred weapon - like a wooden practice sword or an umbrella instead of a real sword. This allows him to show off the fact that he can apply the same techniques with a proper weapon if he chose to do so.\n\nThe fight will usually end before anyone's killed, but only after the person with the weaker weapon has clearly demonstrated his superior fighting technique. This is a route generally taken by pacifists who are good at fighting and want to end a fight without having to actually hurt anyone, though it isn't unusual for a Weak, but Skilled player to take this route. There will probably be a lesson in humility during or after the fight, and the weapon master usually remains humble himself and uses the experience as a teaching opportunity.\n\nContrast Cherry Tapping, where the purpose of picking a weak weapon would be to humiliate their opponent. This is usually why Wooden Katanas Are Even Better; the weapon isn't better, but the user of the weak weapon is usually stronger. Also contrast Improbable Weapon User, someone who regularly arms themselves with wacky weapons, and Once Killed a Man with a Noodle Implement, where a character brags about or is rumored to have fought someone with an improbable weapon. See also Improvised Weapon.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheManMakesTheWeapon", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IpMan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/JackieChan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/JackieChan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/RevolutionaryGirlUtena", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/OnePiece", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/TenjhoTenge", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/RurouniKenshin", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Trigun", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/DragonBallZ", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/TokyoGhoul", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/KenichiTheMightiestDisciple", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Naruto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/SwordArtOnline", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/ThunderboltFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/YuushaNiNarenakattaOreWaShibushibuShuushokuOKetsuiShimashita", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Gamaran", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/CrouchingTigerHiddenDragon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Fearless2006", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IpMan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/GameOfDeath", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheChroniclesOfRiddick", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/GodOfCookery", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/JackieChan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheTwilightSamurai", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/OnceUponATimeInChina", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IronMonkey", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AlexanderNevsky", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/SevenSamurai", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheWheelOfTime", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/FateZero", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Nasuverse", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/FateZero", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VisualNovel/FateStayNight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Leverage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/DeadliestWarrior", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MartialLaw", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheMusketeers", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/DoctorWho", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/PeterCapaldi", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheMusketeers", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/SpiritOfTheCentury", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/Risus", "/pmwiki/pmw